Deputy National Security Advisor Benjamin Rhodes met with Burma's Speaker of the Lower House of Parliament, Shwe Mann, at the White House. They discussed the work of the Parliament and current efforts toward democratic reform in Burma. Rhodes reiterated the U.S. commitment to deepen bilateral engagement as the reform effort moves forward. They also discussed progress made towards a national ceasefire agreement and the need for political dialogue to achieve a lasting peace. They talked about preparations for inclusive national elections and the importance of credible constitutional reform. Rhodes raised concerns about the draft "Laws to Protect Race and Religion" and emphasized the need for equal protections for all of Burma's diverse peoples, including religious minorities. He also underscored the urgent need to fulfill the government's commitments to improve the lives of those affected by the humanitarian crisis in Rakhine State. Rhodes emphasized President Obama's personal commitment to supporting the reform process and engagement between the two countries.